{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "This paper considers three general dilemmas that tend to undermine successful configurations of unity: the either/or dilemma, the synthesis dilemma and the relativism dilemma.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "It further argues that, in his aesthetic writings, Schiller's critique of Kantian dualisms leads him to an adualistic conception of unity that operates with a different, more inclusive approach to opposition and unification.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Entities that are undeniably different from one another proves problematic because of what I want to call the three dilemmas of unification: the either/or dilemma, the synthesis dilemma and the relativist dilemma.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "When unity is established via an either/or decision, out of the various alternative models, one model (for example, the German federal model) becomes binding for all participants.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "A unity based on such an either/or decision is likely to generate discontent, the differences return, and conflict is likely to reappear.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "When unity is established via a synthesis, the participating groups usually agree on a middle ground.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Either this leads to a 'lowest common denominator' which is quickly perceived to be unsatisfactory, or, when the goal is an identity beyond differences, there is no longer an incentive for the groups to be responsive to one another.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The relativist dilemma occurs when all participants demand equal validity for themselves and their context, and despite a formal unity, none of the groups requires the other to secure its own identity.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Again, the result is an increased alienation that frustrates the desired unification.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Schiller avoids the either/or alternative because 'Der bloss niedergeworfene Feind kann wieder auferstehen, aber der versöhnte Feind ist wahrhaft überwunden' (NA, XX, 284; my emphasis).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Schiller himself prefers an adualistic logic, where both opposed poles remain separate and yet united.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Traditionally, we expect to find unity when all differences and contradictions have been resolved.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Schiller's texts instruct us that what is required for 'a firm basis' might be the realization that, in order to be together, it is necessary to remain separate; in order to become one, it is necessary to remain different.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
